   =20
      Bankruptcy procedure
   =20
 =20

We talked above about FTX=E2=80=99s Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing in Delawar=
e, but actually things are a bit more complicated than that. FTX =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0under its new CEO, John Ray =E2=80=94=C2=A0has filed a voluntary Chap=
ter 11 bankruptcy petition in Delaware. But there is a competing bankruptcy=
: Last week Bahamian regulators put FTX=E2=80=99s Bahamas legal entity, FTX=
 Digital Markets, into liquidation and  appointed joint provisional liquida=
tors, and those liquidators have filed a Chapter 15 US bankruptcy case in N=
ew York.
  [6]
 There is some dispute about which case =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one led by FTX=
=E2=80=99s current management, or the one led by its home regulators =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is the correct and controlling bankruptcy. On the one hand, the Ba=
hamian regulators  think FTX=E2=80=99s Delaware filing was not quite legal:

Bahamas-based lawyer Brian Simms, one of the provisional liquidators appoin=
ted by the Bahamas Supreme Court, said in a court filing that FTX was not a=
uthorized to file for bankruptcy in the U.S., adding that he =E2=80=9Crejec=
t[s] the validity of any purported attempt to place FTX affiliates in bankr=
uptcy.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
Though Simms did not ask the court to dismiss the U.S. bankruptcy proceedin=
gs, he requested that the court recognize the validity of the Bahamian lega=
l actions, which he said could =E2=80=9Cimpact=E2=80=9D U.S. proceedings fo=
r the other FTX-controlled entities.

That impact, Simms essentially argued in his declaration, boils down to thi=
s: FTX Digital Markets was the parent company of the entire FTX empire =E2=
=80=93 and all of that empire=E2=80=99s assets ultimately belong to FTX Dig=
ital Markets. ...
Simms has asked the court for provisional relief including the recognition =
of Bahamian bankruptcy and liquidation proceedings, and orders entrusting F=
TX=E2=80=99s assets located in the U.S. to Bahamian liquidators, authorizin=
g =E2=80=9Curgent discovery measures,=E2=80=9D and preventing any of FTX=E2=
=80=99s assets to be =E2=80=9Ctransfer[ed], encumber[ed] or otherwise dispo=
se[d] of.=E2=80=9D

On the other hand, FTX=E2=80=99s management  filed a motion in the Delaware=
 bankruptcy case today arguing that the Delaware case should control and th=
at the Bahamas joint provisional liquidators (=E2=80=9CJPLs=E2=80=9D) shoul=
d not have filed their case in New York. In some sense this is a boring dis=
pute over court procedures, over which lawyers and which legal system shoul=
d be in charge.=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s lawyers write:
Basic principles of efficient judicial administration and effective coordin=
ation argue strongly in favor of all U.S. proceedings relating to the FTX g=
roup occurring in a single U.S. court=E2=80=94this Court. Having two bankru=
ptcy courts consider related issues simply makes no sense. It would result =
in potentially inconsistent opinions, duplication of efforts, and unnecessa=
ry expense.
Fine, boring, normal. But FTX=E2=80=99s lawyers go on:

Mr. Bankman-Fried, the co-founder, and controlling owner of all of the Debt=
ors and of FTX DM, appears to be supporting efforts by the JPLs to expand t=
he scope of the FTX DM proceeding in the Bahamas, to undermine these Chapte=
r 11 Cases, and to move assets from the Debtors to accounts in the Bahamas =
under the control of the Bahamian government. In verified messages posted t=
hrough Twitter,
  [7]
=C2=A0Mr. Bankman-Fried just yesterday expressed profane disdain for regula=
tors, his regrets at these Chapter 11 Cases having been filed, and disclose=
d his goal that =E2=80=9Cwe win a jurisdictional battle vs. Delaware=E2=80=
=9D to have any proceedings occur in the Bahamas. ...
In addition, in connection with investigating a hack on Sunday, November 13=
, Mr. Bankman-Fried and Mr. Wang stated in recorded and verified texts that=
 =E2=80=9CBahamas regulators=E2=80=9D instructed that certain post-petition=
 transfers of Debtor assets be made by Mr. Wang and Mr. Bankman-Fried (who =
the Debtors understand were both effectively in the custody of Bahamas auth=
orities) and that such assets were =E2=80=9Ccustodied on FireBlocks under c=
ontrol of Bahamian gov=E2=80=99t=E2=80=9D.
The Debtors thus have credible evidence that the Bahamian government is res=
ponsible for directing unauthorized access to the Debtors=E2=80=99 systems =
for the purpose of obtaining digital assets of the Debtors=E2=80=94that too=
k place after the commencement of these cases.=C2=A0The appointment of the =
JPLs and recognition of the Chapter 15 Case are thus in serious question. I=
t appears that the automatic stay has been flaunted, by a government actor =
no less.

I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what? Is the claim here that the Bahamian government is wo=
rking for Bankman-Fried? That Bankman-Fried is working for the Bahamian gov=
ernment? That, in either case, Bankman-Fried and Bahamian regulators conspi=
red to hack FTX to drain customer money before FTX=E2=80=99s bankruptcy man=
agement could get their hands on it?
I assume not; I assume this is mostly a jurisdictional dispute about which =
set of lawyers and regulators and judges should supervise the money, and th=
at the Bahamian government would disagree that their efforts to access and =
secure FTX=E2=80=99s money were =E2=80=9Cunauthorized.=E2=80=9D But there d=
oes seem to be a certain amount of distrust. Bankman-Fried and other (forme=
r) FTX executives are Americans, and FTX was headquartered in the Bahamas n=
ot because it was founded there but because the Bahamas offered a friendlie=
r regulatory environment than the US did. Now that FTX is bust, its lawyers=
 might worry that the regulatory environment in the Bahamas was too friendl=
y.

