One thing that I   like to   say around here is that it is good for your ca=
reer, in finance, to lose a billion dollars. Losing a billion dollars indic=
ates, to your next employer or investors, that someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0presu=
mably someone smart, who had a billion dollars =E2=80=94=C2=A0trusted you w=
ith a billion dollars. It shows that you had the ability and nerve to take =
risks, which is (within reason) an attractive quality in high finance. And =
presumably you learned valuable lessons about whatever went wrong, and next=
 time you will take=C2=A0better=C2=A0risks and=C2=A0make=C2=A0a lot of mone=
y instead of losing it.
I think of this as applying mostly to traders at big banks and hedge funds,=
 but it has broader applicability. Adam Neumann incinerated truly titanic a=
mounts of investor money at WeWork Inc., which was bad, and got him removed=
 as chief executive officer of WeWork. But it was also =E2=80=A6=C2=A0impre=
ssive? And so if you are an investor, and Adam Neumann calls you and says =
=E2=80=9Chey can you put money into my new thing,=E2=80=9D you might think =
thoughts like:
=09I should take this meeting, it will be funny.=09Adam Neumann has experie=
nce running a very large fast-growing business. Into the ground, yes, but n=
ot everyone has that experience.=09Probably he learned some lessons and won=
=E2=80=99t incinerate=C2=A0my=C2=A0money.

Also, the charm that Neumann used to raise money last time might work on yo=
u this time, even though you know what happened last time. And so in fact N=
eumann has done pretty well at   raising money for his next thing. Losing a=
=C2=A0lot=C2=A0of money, very quickly, in a very high-profile way, with a s=
ense of style, can help you raise more money.
We talked above about Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s  direct message exchange =
with Kelsey Piper at Vox. It touches on FTX=E2=80=99s accounting. But it al=
so touches on Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s path forward. =E2=80=9CI have two wee=
ks to raise $8b,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s basically all th=
at matters for the rest of my life.=E2=80=9D Piper replies: =E2=80=9CWell, =
I really hope that the depositors get the money back, but I gotta say, I ha=
ve no idea how anyone could possibly pull that off from this starting point=
.=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried:

well a month ago I was one of the world=E2=80=99s greatest fundraisers
now I=E2=80=99m the fallen wreckage of one
but there=E2=80=99s a thing about being fallen=E2=80=94
there are people who know what that=E2=80=99s like, and who want to do for =
someone else what nobody did for them

Honestly a good line! I want to see where this goes. My guess is that he is=
 too aggressive about the timeline: You can lose $8 billion, pause to refle=
ct for a year or two,=C2=A0and then come back strong to raise billions more=
. But Bankman-Fried is probably right that he does not have that kind of ti=
me, so he=E2=80=99s trying to raise a huge pile of money while still in the=
 process of losing his first huge pile of money.=C2=A0
Elsewhere, the Wall Street Journal reports on  FTX=E2=80=99s employees=E2=
=80=99 reaction to the bankruptcy:

What started as a dream job turned into a nightmare for employees of FTX, t=
he crypto exchange that imploded in spectacular fashion last week. The Wall=
 Street Journal spoke to more than a dozen current and former employees, ma=
ny of whom said they were stunned by FTX=E2=80=99s swift demise and shocked=
 by the alleged misuse of customer funds. =E2=80=A6
Ryan Salame, co-chief executive of the exchange=E2=80=99s Bahamas-based uni=
t FTX Digital Markets, told people close to him that he became physically s=
ick and threw up when he became aware of FTX=E2=80=99s problems early last =
week, the people said. Although he worked closely with Mr. Bankman-Fried, M=
r. Salame wasn=E2=80=99t part of the inner circle around FTX=E2=80=99s lead=
er, the people said. =E2=80=A6
Dozens of FTX employees quit last week, including senior figures such as he=
ad of product Ramnik Arora, chief regulatory officer Dan Friedberg and head=
 of institutional sales Zane Tackett, people familiar with the matter said.=
 One employee said he submitted his resignation to his boss, only for the b=
oss to say he had already resigned himself.
A friend of Mr. Friedberg=E2=80=99s who had dinner with him the day he quit=
 said the attorney=E2=80=94previously a big admirer of Mr. Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=94was visibly shaken.=C2=A0
Mr. Friedberg showed this friend the text message he sent to Mr. Bankman-Fr=
ied and other top FTX executives submitting his resignation. In the message=
, the friend recalled, Mr. Friedberg described himself as devastated and sa=
id: =E2=80=9COne day I hope I can forgive you.=E2=80=9D

On the one hand, it does seem like FTX was what you=E2=80=99d get if a half=
-dozen college buddies ran a global financial exchange with no supervision.=
 On the other hand, there were in fact hundreds of employees, including a c=
hief regulatory officer. They resigned in shock when they learned about FTX=
=E2=80=99s insolvency and its misuse of customer money. But presumably they=
 knew about the =E2=80=A6=C2=A0emojis in the chats? It is one thing for a s=
mall group of top executives, who all live with each other, to do intention=
al fraud and keep it secret from the rest of the company. But the =E2=80=9C=
complete failure of corporate controls and =E2=80=A6 complete absence of tr=
ustworthy financial information=E2=80=9D seems like something someone might=
 have noticed.

