<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bankruptcy procedure</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked above about FTX=E2=80=99s Chapter 11=
 bankruptcy filing in Delaware, but actually things are a bit more complica=
ted than that. FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0under its new CEO, John Ray =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0has filed a voluntary Chapter 11 bankruptcy petition in Delaware. But th=
ere is a competing bankruptcy: Last week Bahamian regulators put FTX=E2=80=
=99s Bahamas legal entity, FTX Digital Markets, into liquidation and <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29730538.256530/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL3BvbGljeS8yMDIyLzExLzE1L2JhaGFtaWFuLXN1cHJlbWUtY29=
1cnQtYXBwcm92ZXMtbGlxdWlkYXRvcnMtZm9yLWZ0eC1hc3NldHMv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB0b366d37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> appointed joint provisional liquidators</a>, and tho=
se liquidators have filed a Chapter 15 US bankruptcy case in New York.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> There is some dispute about which case =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one led by F=
TX=E2=80=99s current management, or the one led by its home regulators =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is the correct and controlling bankruptcy. On the one hand, the=
 Bahamian regulators <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/29730538.256530/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL3BvbGljeS8yMDIyLzExLzE2=
L2JhaGFtaWFuLWxpcXVpZGF0b3JzLXNheS1mdHgtd2FzbnQtYXV0aG9yaXplZC10by1maWxlLWZ=
vci1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LWluLXRoZS11cy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB749aa5e2" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> think FTX=E2=80=99s Delaware filing was not quite legal</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bahamas-based lawyer Brian Simms, one of the p=
rovisional liquidators appointed by the Bahamas Supreme Court, said in a co=
urt filing that FTX was not authorized to file for bankruptcy in the U.S., =
adding that he =E2=80=9Creject[s] the validity of any purported attempt to =
place FTX affiliates in bankruptcy.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though Simms did not ask the court to dismiss =
the U.S. bankruptcy proceedings, he requested that the court recognize the =
validity of the Bahamian legal actions, which he said could =E2=80=9Cimpact=
=E2=80=9D U.S. proceedings for the other FTX-controlled entities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That impact, Simms essentially argued in his d=
eclaration, boils down to this: FTX Digital Markets was the parent company =
of the entire FTX empire =E2=80=93 and all of that empire=E2=80=99s assets =
ultimately belong to FTX Digital Markets. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simms has asked the court for provisional reli=
ef including the recognition of Bahamian bankruptcy and liquidation proceed=
ings, and orders entrusting FTX=E2=80=99s assets located in the U.S. to Bah=
amian liquidators, authorizing =E2=80=9Curgent discovery measures,=E2=80=9D=
 and preventing any of FTX=E2=80=99s assets to be =E2=80=9Ctransfer[ed], en=
cumber[ed] or otherwise dispose[d] of.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, FTX=E2=80=99s management <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29730538.256530/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9wYWNlci1kb2N1bWVudHMuczMuYW1hem9uYXdzLmNvbS8zMy8xODg0NTAvMDQyMTIwNjQ=
4MTg2LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a2513f0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> filed a motion</a> =
in the Delaware bankruptcy case today arguing that the Delaware case should=
 control and that the Bahamas joint provisional liquidators (=E2=80=9CJPLs=
=E2=80=9D) should not have filed their case in New York. In some sense this=
 is a boring dispute over court procedures, over which lawyers and which le=
gal system should be in charge.=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s lawyers write:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basic principles of efficient judi=
cial administration and effective coordination argue strongly in favor of a=
ll U.S. proceedings relating to the FTX group occurring in a single U.S. co=
urt=E2=80=94this Court. Having two bankruptcy courts consider related issue=
s simply makes no sense. It would result in potentially inconsistent opinio=
ns, duplication of efforts, and unnecessary expense.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine, boring, normal. But FTX=E2=80=99s lawyer=
s go on:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Bankman-Fried, the co-founder, and control=
ling owner of all of the Debtors and of FTX DM, appears to be supporting ef=
forts by the JPLs to expand the scope of the FTX DM proceeding in the Baham=
as, to undermine these Chapter 11 Cases, and to move assets from the Debtor=
s to accounts in the Bahamas under the control of the Bahamian government. =
In verified messages posted through Twitter,<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Mr. Bankman-Fried just yesterday expressed profane disdain for re=
gulators, his regrets at these Chapter 11 Cases having been filed, and disc=
losed his goal that =E2=80=9Cwe win a jurisdictional battle vs. Delaware=E2=
=80=9D to have any proceedings occur in the Bahamas. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition, in connection with investigating =
a hack on Sunday, November 13, Mr. Bankman-Fried and Mr. Wang stated in rec=
orded and verified texts that =E2=80=9CBahamas regulators=E2=80=9D instruct=
ed that certain post-petition transfers of Debtor assets be made by Mr. Wan=
g and Mr. Bankman-Fried (who the Debtors understand were both effectively i=
n the custody of Bahamas authorities) and that such assets were =E2=80=9Ccu=
stodied on FireBlocks under control of Bahamian gov=E2=80=99t=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Debtors thus have credible evidence that t=
he Bahamian government is responsible for directing unauthorized access to =
the Debtors=E2=80=99 systems for the purpose of obtaining digital assets of=
 the Debtors=E2=80=94that took place <em>after </em>the commencement of the=
se cases.=C2=A0The appointment of the JPLs and recognition of the Chapter 1=
5 Case are thus in serious question. It appears that the automatic stay has=
 been flaunted, by a government actor no less.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what? Is the claim here that =
the Bahamian government is working for Bankman-Fried? That Bankman-Fried is=
 working for the Bahamian government? That, in either case, Bankman-Fried a=
nd Bahamian regulators conspired to hack FTX to drain customer money before=
 FTX=E2=80=99s bankruptcy management could get their hands on it?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume not; I assume this is mostly a jurisd=
ictional dispute about which set of lawyers and regulators and judges shoul=
d supervise the money, and that the Bahamian government would disagree that=
 their efforts to access and secure FTX=E2=80=99s money were =E2=80=9Cunaut=
horized.=E2=80=9D But there does seem to be a certain amount of distrust. B=
ankman-Fried and other (former) FTX executives are Americans, and FTX was h=
eadquartered in the Bahamas not because it was founded there but because th=
e Bahamas offered a friendlier regulatory environment than the US did. Now =
that FTX is bust, its lawyers might worry that the regulatory environment i=
n the Bahamas was too friendly.</p>
